## 1. Hard Rules (non-negotiable)

1. **Secrets stay out of git.** Never commit `.env`,
   `credentials.json`, API keys, or any file matching `*secret*`. If
   you spot one already committed, stop and ask before touching
   anything else.
2. **Destructive git ops require explicit instruction.** Never run
   `git reset --hard`, `git push --force`, `git branch -D`, or
   `git clean -f` unless the user named the command in this session.
3. **Project-internal references use relative paths.** Anything that
   points inside this repo: no drive-letter prefixes (a letter plus
   colon), no tilde home shortcuts, no absolute user-home directories
   — use repo-relative paths or `${PROJECT_ROOT}` indirection, so the
   docs survive a clone to any machine. Absolute paths ARE allowed
   when the reference is genuinely environment-bound (another local
   repo, a system service, a tool install location) — but mark the
   line with a `(local-env)` tag so readers know it will not travel.
4. **Durable agent state lives in `.agent_works/`.** Ephemeral scratch
   goes to `.local/` (gitignored). Never put durable state in
   `.local/`; never put session scratch in `.agent_works/`. The
   dot-prefix on `.agent_works/` signals "this is meta, not code" —
   IDE file trees hide it by default, but it is committed to git.
5. **Describe the system as it is today** — in user-facing docs
   especially. In `README.md`, `AGENTS.md`, and anything else humans
   or agents read to onboard, never write "previously", "no longer",
   "now uses", or "is still" — that is version-history rot, and the
   next reader has no way to date the claim. Git history is the
   archive. (Internal session state like `current_handoff.md` can
   still narrate recent transitions when useful.)
6. **Stop and ask when blocked** by permissions, missing credentials,
   or a heavy setup step. Do not invent product decisions silently.
7. **Never delete cross-agent pointer files** — `CLAUDE.md`,
   `GEMINI.md`, `AGENT.md`, or any symlink / one-line pointer
   resolving to `AGENTS.md` — unless the user explicitly asks. They
   are the entry points other agents use; removing one silently
   breaks that runtime's onboarding.
8. **Environment isolation.** Never install packages or run
   verifications in the base / global environment. Use a
   project-dedicated env (`.venv`, conda env from `environment.yaml`,
   project-local `node_modules`, etc.) — whatever the language uses.
   On Windows, avoid the `C:` drive for large deps and model weights
   to prevent disk pressure.

