## 6. Code Conventions

- **Default to no comments.** Add a comment only when the *why* is
  non-obvious (a workaround, a hidden constraint, surprising behavior).
  Well-named identifiers explain the *what*.
- **No error handling for impossible scenarios.** Validate at system
  boundaries (user input, external APIs); trust framework guarantees
  inside. Do not catch exceptions you cannot act on.
- **No features beyond what the task requires.** A bug fix does not
  need surrounding cleanup. A one-shot operation does not need a
  helper. No half-finished implementations.
- **No backwards-compat shims for unreleased code.** If a name
  changes, rename it. Do not re-export the old name "just in case".

---

## 7. Communication With the User

The user does not carry your full context or remember every prior
decision the way you do. Speak accordingly.

- **No bare codenames or internal IDs.** Never cite `D-073`,
  `TP-082`, `Phase H`, `Milestone G`, `v5_rerank`, or any module
  shorthand without a one-line description of what it refers to.
  "Per D-073 we capped X" → "Per D-073 (the 2026-04 retry-budget cap)
  we capped X". The user does not have the decision log memorized;
  opaque codes force a lookup before they can engage.
- **Explain technology and acronyms on first use.** Spell out before
  short-forming. "We switched to RPC" → "We switched the inter-process
  call layer to RPC (HTTP+JSON over a local socket)"; the short form
  is fine after the explanation.
- **Concrete over abstract.** "performance is better" leaves the user
  guessing. Show the difference — "p50 dropped from 240ms to 90ms on
  the smoke task". A specific number, file path, or diff beats a
  general adjective every time.
- **Annotate code snippets.** When pasting code, add an inline comment
  on any variable or field whose meaning is not self-evident inside
  the snippet. The user reads without your full file context — what
  is obvious to you may be opaque to them. Do not make them grep.
- **Plain speech over jargon.** A status update should read like a
  sentence said aloud, not a Slack-of-acronyms. If you would have to
  look up the meaning in six months, rewrite it now.

